Introduction

In today’s modern age of intense international competition, our group wanted to better understand how national expenditure on education correlated to international university rankings, if at all. To that end, we found data sets that gave us international university rankings, as well as data sets that gave us national expenditure on education in 36 different countries.

After much analysis, we found that national expenditure on education is not correlated with that country’s average university world ranking. In technical terms, we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that a country’s average university world ranking is not correlated at all with that country’s expenditure on higher education.

Background

Finding The Data

Our team began by searching Kaggle.com for data on international university rankings and national expenditure on education. On Kaggle, we found Myles O’Neill’s repository of World University Rankings data.1 From this repository, we used three data sets.

University Ranking Data Sets

For the first of these data sets, we used the Center for World University Rankings (CWUR) data.2 There is information for the years 2012, 2013, 2014, and 2015. In 2014 and 2015, 1,000 Universities were ranked, unlike the previous two years that ranked the top 100 Universities instead. The data contains information such as the rank of the institution, name, country, rank within the country, etc.

Next, we have a data set from the Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU), in which the Shanghai Ranking Consultancy gives their own list of University rankings.3 The data includes information from the year 2005 to 2015. The dataset contains the world rank of the institution, name, rank within country, ‘score’ of University, etc.

Our last data set of world ranks was obtained from Times Higher Education World University Ranking (Times Ranking).4 The data includes information from 2011 through 2016. Unlike the ShanghaiRanking, Times Ranking allows the possibility of ‘tying’, where a University’s rank can be shared with another University, but only occurs outside of the top 100 Universities ranked. The data includes the same information as the previous dataset, but includes scores that are broken down; such as an international score, research score, citation score, income score, and total score. Not all countries are in each dataset, as it depends on the institution that created the ranking.

Expenditure Data

We used three additional data sets for our analysis. Borrowing from the work O’Neill had already done, we sought out the root of the expenditure data he had found. This data came from the United States’ National Center for Education Statistics’ 2014 Digest of Education Statistics.5 It includes data for each of the 34 countries that were in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) in 2014, as well as data from Brazil and the Russian Federation. To this, we also added data from the 2019 Digest of Education Statistics. Each of these included data from 3 years ago (2011 and 2016 data respectively), with expenditure measured as a percentage of the country’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP). We pulled out this 2011 and 2016 spending data for each country in the OECD from the three data sets.

Preparing The Data

The first step with our data was to clean and prepare it for analysis.

As mentioned above, we decided to only consider national spending on higher education in 2011 and 2016. These are the years we found spending data to be the most recent and complete from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).

Regarding the three different ranking systems, our goal was to combine them in some way, so that any biases in the rankings could be averaged out. To that end, we decided on a three step process for merging the rankings:

  1. Group each university by the country it is in.

  2. Find the average ranking for each country in each data set.

  3. Find the average country ranking between the three data sets.

We decided on this process because there were too many semantic differences in the university names between the three rankings (for example, the CWUR and Times data refer to our school as “University of Wisconsin-Madison”, while the Shanghai data refer to “University of Wiscosin - Madison”. Since the spacing is different, the terms would not match). Without manually ensuring each school was listed the same in each data set, we could not ensure each university matched. However, the country names were easy to confirm as exactly the same between data sets. Thus, by finding the average rank of each country per data set, we could avoid the issue of university names not matching between data sets.

It is also important to note that we decided to focus our attention on the top 100 universities from each ranking system for each year in which data was provided, and no universities below the top 100. The reason for this is that each ranking organization treated institutions below the top 100 differently (the CWUR data ranked the top 1000 universities, while the Shanghai data gave a range of rankings for those ranked below 100, and the Times data allowed for tied scores below the 100 ranking). In order to avoid any errors that might arise from these incongruities, we selected only the top 100 universities from each data set.

A final note regarding the cleaning of our data is that the Shanghai data set did not include a column for the university’s country. However, with us only considering the top 100 institutions from that data set, it was more reasonable for us to add this column to the data set manually. We did so by pulling university and country pairs from the CWUR data (as the largest data set, it had the most pairs), and matching university names with the Shanghai data. While there were a number of semantic disagreements between the two data sets, we manually overcame them and moved forward.

Having cut the data from each ranking agency down to their top 100 universities in each year for which data was available, and found each country’s average rank, we merged this data together using country and year as a key and found the average world ranking of each country’s institutions throughout all the years for which ranking data was included.

We then filtered out countries from this data that were not members of the OECD (as we only had data on OECD member countries), and adjoined to this remaining list the education spending of each country in 2011 and 2016.

We now had a data table from which we could properly do analysis. The first ten rows of this table are included to further elucidate understanding of our methods:

“NA” values represent years in which spending data was not available due to the country not being a current member of the OECD.

We had one final question from our data: what if there was a delayed effect? That is, what if spending in 2011 had a correlation with a rank improvement in a year later than 2011 that was stronger than the correlation within that same year? Was there any evidence of a delayed correlation, of spending in 2011 really making a difference in another year? We took a look:

This graph compares each country’s 2011 higher education expenditure amount (as a percentage of GDP) to its average university ranking for each year from 2012 to 2015 (further discussion of the regression occurs in the Discussion section).

With our graphical analysis concluded, we needed to see just how strong any correlations were. Using least mean squares analysis, we calculated the estimate of the slope for each of the above graphs, as well as a p-value for that estimate. We put these values into the following table:

Another Computation Method

Though the averaging method seems to land us on the conclusion that expenditure is not a conclusive predictor of University ranking, and even turns out to be negatively correlated, we recognize that taking the average could lead to some biases such as underestimating the ranking score for countries with significantly more universities than the United States (for example, if Korea has only one university making into the top 100, and US has many more, the US may end up getting a worse average world-ranking score). To add on to our analysis and serve as additional evidence, we redefined the metric of how a country fares in its higher education to be a ratio ranking score from the ratio of top 100 universities for each country multiplied by the ratio oftotal number of universities each country has compared to world universities. The second ratio is meant to counterbalance the underestimating effect from certain countries being oversampled in the top 100 so that countries with more universities will get potentially higher ranking scores.

After filtering the countries we have in Universities.tsv (the one in which has the number of universities in each ranking range for countries) 6, we end up with 12 countries and plot their ranking ratio score against their expenditure from year 2013 to 2016 respectively. Discussion

From our analysis, we conclude that national expenditure on education does not strongly correlate with a country’s average university world ranking.

We make this conclusion based on the large p-values for the LMS analysis of average world ranking against expenditure. None of the calculated p-values are below 0.1, and thus none of the estimated slope values are statistically significant.

This conclusion is further supported when weighing country ranks against the number of universities in that country. The fact that these p-values are also large further leads us to accept a null hypothesis, that there is no correlation.

While we trust in our analysis, we do recognize there are a number of areas for improvement, and also that some of our assumptions may be faulty. It is important to note from the beginning that no data source is ever perfectly clean, or composed of all the data we might like to have. Since we only had expenditure datas for certain countries, other countries with exceptional universities were left out of our analysis, such as China and India. As far as our assumptions are concerned, averaging the rankings between three organizations may have some inherent flaws to it, since each organization uses different criteria to create their rankings. Some of this could be overcome by comparing expenditure to each criteria, and seeing which of those criteria is most or least affected by expenditure. This is yet another avenue for further study.

In conclusion, there is much to be learned about how expenditure affects worldwide university rankings, but we feel confident in saying that expenditure is not the most conclusive predictor of an educational institution’s success.
